<%= stream_react_component("NativeMetadataApp",
                         props: @app_props_server_render,
                         prerender: true,
                         trace: true,
                         id: "NativeMetadataApp-react-component-0") %>

<hr/>

<h2>About This Example</h2>
<p>
  This page uses <code>stream_react_component</code> (streaming SSR) with React 19's native
  <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;meta&gt;</code> tags.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>How it works:</strong> The shell renders immediately with the initial title
  "Loading... | React on Rails". When the Suspense boundary resolves (~1s later),
  the async content streams to the browser along with scripts that update the
  <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> in the document <code>&lt;head&gt;</code>.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Trade-off:</strong> The <em>final</em> metadata from inside the Suspense boundary is
  NOT in <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> in the initial server-rendered HTML. The initial title
  ("Loading... | React on Rails") rendered outside the Suspense boundary is hoisted into
  the shell, but the resolved title from the async content arrives later via React 19's
  hoisting scripts in the streamed chunks. SEO crawlers that don't execute JavaScript will
  see only the initial title, not the resolved one.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Compare with:</strong>
  <%= link_to "Sync SSR version", native_metadata_path %> |
  <%= link_to "RSC version", rsc_native_metadata_path %> |
  <%= link_to "Hybrid approach (recommended for SEO)", hybrid_metadata_streaming_path %> |
  <%= link_to "Helmet approach (react_component_hash)", react_helmet_path %>
</p>
